title: For Sale:  Chiappa Firearms RHINO 20DS 357 MAG RBH Knife
postcontent: The new Chiappa Rhino has revolutionized the revolver with a patented design that tames the prehistoric characteristic that most revolvers possess. The new Chiappa Rhino barrel is aligned with the bottom most chamber which is the key component to Rhino's tame characteristics. The position of the barrel lowers the center of gravity and yields a centerline of the bore more in line with the shooter's arm allowing for the most natural "point ability" while engaging a target. This characteristic also drastically reduces both recoil and muzzle flip which insures subsequent shots to be on target faster than ever before. The reduction of the recoil allows for the use of ultra light alloys to be used in the construction of the Rhino minimizing any adverse effect. The flat sided cylinder design of the Rhino reduces the typical revolver profile allowing greater concealment. With choices from 2" to 6" barrel lengths and sight options, the Rhino is truly a multipurpose handgun capable of reliable defensive duty, scoring ten rings, and taking game. Featuring both double and single action characteristics, the single action is actuated by a hammer cocking device that engages the unexposed hammer to prepare to fire.

However, I do require an IN photo ID and an IN LTCH be provided by those I meet, or it will prove to be a wasted trip for both of us unless we use an FFL holder to transfer the firearm at the buyer's expense.

Extra items that can be included in a larger package deal are three 17 round nickel plated Mec-Gar magazines, and three blued 17 round Mec-Gar magazines at $10.00 each. Also, four Mec-Gar 18 round magazines can be included for $20.00 each. [If sold separately, the individual price for the six 17 round magazines is $20.00. And the individual price for the four 18 round magazines is $30.00.] If all of the listed magazines are included in the package, this will raise the total price to $590.00 plus the $20.00 FFL fee (Total: $610.00).

The only problem I experienced with this particular PT-99 is with the rear sight blade, which came loose from the sight assembly... No, I can assure prospective buyers that this pistol was never dropped or otherwise abused. In fact, I solved this problem by inserting a small piece of barely discernable polymer tubing under the rear sight blade. This action not only fully secured the sight blade but does not prevent it from being adjusted. A new rear sight assembly can always be purchased from Taurus if the new owner so desires.

Only those who want to purchase this pistol and accessories will receive a response from me, since I'm tired of being annoyed by those who have no intention of actually buying the items I'm selling. 

Prospective buyers who wish to use an FFL holder must supply me with their full name and FFL mailing address and phone number (NO TEXTING) within twenty-four hours, or I will consider the transaction null and void. [Indiana residents who want to meet with me must supply me with their full name, phone number (NO TEXTING), and the public place and time during daylight hours they want to meet to conduct the transaction.] Once I receive the required information, I will supply the buyer who wants the items shipped with my full name and mailing address where they can send payment in full via money order. Once I receive payment in full, I will then notify buyer when their order has shipped.

My prices and terms are not negotiable.

title: For Sale:  SOLD: British 1863 .577 Snider-Enfield Hinged Breech Rifle
postcontent: This British 1863 .577 Snider-Enfield hinged breech block infantry rifle finish has turned mottled gray/brown patina, but nothing out of the ordinary for its age and commensurate usage. The screw heads are sharp and not disfigured. The markings are clear and sharp. The wood has dings and dents, but no cracks or repairs. The action and lock both function positively. British proof marked, the lock plate is marked 1863 ENFIELD with crown and VR. The stock shows an Enfield cartouche, British not Indian. It has a 36" barrel, a long range folding ladder rear sight with a blade front sight, cleaning rod, 3 barrel bands, 2 sling swivels, is chambered for the .577 Snider, with no serial number. The British .577 Snider-Enfield action was invented by the American Jacob Snider, to convert the vast stocks of otherwise obsolete 1853 Enfield muzzle loaders in the British inventory. It was introduced in 1866, and was used by the British Army until it was superseded by the Martini-Henry rifle in 1871. The Snider-Enfield was used by the British Indian Army almost to the end of the nineteenth century. The rifle is at our shop on consignment, so we are unable to consider trades. Shipping to your local FFL dealer is available for an additional charge.

only 1600 maintained miles.  No wheelies, but I have taken it up to 140mph on one occasion.  Followed the proper break in procedure however.

This is a fine example of a RARE N Frame Smith & Wesson in .357 Magnum.

Smith & Wesson produced this revolver for the New York State Police in 1980. NYSP went a different direction, cancelled the order, and Smith sold the revolvers on the civilian market.
